<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 8:22<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27da1d50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>8.</label.designator><headtext>Relevancy</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7201716682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>8:22.</label.designator><headtext>Flight and concealment</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The fact that a person charged with a crime flees after its alleged commission is relevant on the issue of guilt, but has only slight probative value.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7968472074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Evidence that the defendant forfeited his appearance bond is admissible to prove flight.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7968472174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] However, evidence that the defendant voluntarily surrendered and did not flee is not admissible to show his innocence,[<footnote.reference refid="I79686e3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] but will be admissible as rebuttal where the prosecution introduced evidence of flight.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79686e3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] Evidence of flight in connection with other circumstances is sufficient to initiate investigative stop.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79686e3274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><?page no="260"?><bos/><paratext>Evidence of attempts to conceal identity or conduct by a criminal defendant will be relevant on the issue of guilt.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79686e3374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] Furthermore, where a police officer tries to execute an arrest warrant, and the defendant attempts to flee, that is considered circumstantial evidence of guilt.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I79686e3474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1990163869" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27cc9c274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Renner v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I79686e3574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court held that, while the state may offer evidence of and argue flight in a criminal case, it is error for a trial court to charge the jury on flight. <eos/><bos/>In federal courts, evidence of a criminally accused&apos;s flight and evading capture is admissible as evidence of guilt.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7968954074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7968472074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1982108096" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If2796e6274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Pollard v. State, 249 Ga. 21, 287 S.E.2d 189 (1982)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1982108098" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If2796e6574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Anderson v. State, 249 Ga. 132, 287 S.E.2d 195 (1982)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1982126834" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If2796e6874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Miller v. State, 162 Ga. App. 730, 292 S.E.2d 102 (1982)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1997226846" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If2796e6b74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Matthews v. State, 268 Ga. 798, 493 S.E.2d 136 (1997)</cite.query>); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1983132735" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If2796e6e74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hogans v. State, 251 Ga. 242, 304 S.E.2d 699 (1983)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1984108638" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If2796e7174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hodges v. State, 169 Ga. App. 70, 311 S.E.2d 506 (1983)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7968472174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1921103548" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="If27a0aa274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Jones v. State, 26 Ga. App. 635, 107 S.E. 166 (1921)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1927107285" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="If27a0aa574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Woody v. State, 37 Ga. App. 338, 140 S.E. 396 (1927)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79686e3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1940105573" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27a7fd274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Moyers v. State, 61 Ga. App. 324, 6 S.E.2d 438 (1939)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79686e3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1947103979" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27acdf274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Lester v. State, 75 Ga. App. 42, 42 S.E.2d 141 (1947)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79686e3274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="2038432586" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27b432274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Williams, 336 Ga. App. 97, 783 S.E.2d 700 (2016)</cite.query>, <case.history>opinion vacated on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="2043665978" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27b432574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><?page no="260"?>344 Ga. App. 311, 809 S.E.2d 844 (2018)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="2037172035" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27b432874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Quarterman, 333 Ga. App. 803, 777 S.E.2d 485 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79686e3374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1944104243" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27bb85274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Woodward v. State, 197 Ga. 60, 28 S.E.2d 480 (1943)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1943104437" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27bb85574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">James v. State, 68 Ga. App. 765, 24 S.E.2d 149 (1943)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79686e3474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="2034493494" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27c2d8274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Barstad v. State, 329 Ga. App. 214, 764 S.E.2d 453 (2014)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I79686e3574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="1990163869" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If27cf0d274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Renner v. State, 260 Ga. 515, 397 S.E.2d 683 (1990)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7968954074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017147" w-serial-number="2010921055" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="If27d660174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">U.S. v. Kennard, 472 F.3d 851 (11th Cir. 2006)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.c